    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The avalanche prone locations are to be found in particular in steep terrain at intermediate and high altitudes and on steep sunny slopes below approximately 2200 m.</highlights>
      <comment>In particular above approximately 2200 m: Weak layers in the old snowpack can still be released in some place by winter sport participants. This applies in particular on steep west, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Dry avalanches can in isolated cases be released by a single winter sport participant. In the regions exposed to snowfall this applies especially on very steep slopes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> As a consequence of warming during the day and the solar radiation, the likelihood of moist and wet avalanches being released will increase in particular below approximately 2200 m. &lt;br/> Backcountry tours should be started and concluded early.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Monday: In some localities 5 to 15 cm of snow, and up to 20 cm in some localities, has fallen since Monday above approximately 1600 m. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Intermediate and high altitudes: Weak layers exist in the snowpack especially on west, north and northeast facing slopes. In shady places that are protected from the wind: Towards its surface, the snowpack is dry; its surface consists of loosely bonded snow. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. In places that are protected from the wind in all altitude zones a lot of snow is lying for the time of year. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Low and intermediate altitudes and steep sunny slopes: The surface of the snowpack will only just freeze and will soften earlier than the day before. &lt;br/> Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise in the late morning to increasing moistening of the snowpack in particular on sunny slopes in particular at low and intermediate altitudes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
